tely, Panaccio stresses the originality and significance of Ockham's doctrine of the oratio mentalis (mental discourse) and the strong impression it made upon his immediate successors.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aConcepts. 0aKnowledge, Theory ofxHistory. 0aLanguage and logic. 0aLogic. 0aThought and thinkingxHistory. 0aThought and thinking--History. 7aSCIENCE / Cognitive Science.2bisacsh  aThomas Aquinas.  aWilliam Ockham.  aconcept.  alanguage of thought.  amental language.  amental word.  athought.1 aHochschild, Joshua P.1 aZiebart, Meredith K.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311072901640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082327262440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823272624423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823272624.jpg  a978-3-11-072901-6  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK